# Migrating `EventProcessor` to .NET 8

## Key Problems in the Original Code

| .NET Framework API | .NET 8 Status |
|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | **Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** (removed in .NET 5+) |
| `Thread.Interrupt()` | Still works but is a poor cancellation mechanism |
| `ManualResetEvent` + `lock` + `Queue` | Works, but `Channel<T>` replaces all three |
| Race condition: multiple `Enqueue` calls before `Dequeue` | **Bug**: `Reset()` clears signal, losing queued items |

## Migrated Code (.NET 8)

```csharp
using System.Threading.Channels;

public class EventProcessor : IAsyncDisposable
{
    private readonly Channel<string> _channel = Channel.CreateUnbounded<string>();
    private readonly CancellationTokenSource _cts = new();
    private Task? _processTask;

    public void Start()
    {
        _processTask = Task.Run(() => RunLoopAsync(_cts.Token));
    }

    private async Task RunLoopAsync(CancellationToken ct)
    {
        await foreach (var item in _channel.Reader.ReadAllAsync(ct))
        {
            Handle(item);
        }
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item)
    {
        if (!_channel.Writer.TryWrite(item))
            throw new InvalidOperationException("Channel is closed.");
    }

    public async ValueTask DisposeAsync()
    {
        _channel.Writer.Complete();          // signal no more items
        _cts.Cancel();                       // cancel if blocked waiting
        if (_processTask is not null)
            await _processTask.ConfigureAwait(false);  // wait for graceful exit
        _cts.Dispose();
    }

    private void Handle(string item) { /* your logic */ }
}
```

## What Changed and Why

**1. `Thread.Abort()` → `CancellationToken`**
`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` on .NET 5+. Use cooperative cancellation via `CancellationTokenSource` instead.

**2. `Thread.Interrupt()` → `Channel.Writer.Complete()` + cancel**
`Complete()` causes `ReadAllAsync` to finish naturally after draining. The token handles the case where you want to stop immediately.

**3. `ManualResetEvent` + `lock` + `Queue` → `Channel<T>`**
`Channel<T>` is a thread-safe, async-ready producer/consumer queue — it replaces all three primitives and **fixes the race condition** where multiple `Enqueue` calls before a single `Dequeue` would lose items.

**4. `Thread` → `Task.Run`**
Modern .NET idiom; avoids dedicated thread overhead.

## Pitfalls to Watch For

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---|---|
| **Fire-and-forget `Task.Run`** | Always store and await the task, or exceptions vanish silently |
| **Graceful vs. immediate stop** | `Complete()` drains remaining items; `Cancel()` stops immediately. Choose based on your needs — the code above cancels mid-drain |
| **`Handle` throwing** | An unhandled exception kills the loop. Wrap in `try/catch` if partial failures are acceptable |
| **Bounded vs. unbounded** | `CreateUnbounded` can cause OOM under pressure. Use `CreateBounded(capacity)` with backpressure if needed |
| **Synchronous callers** | If callers can't use `await DisposeAsync()`, expose a synchronous `Stop()` that calls `.GetAwaiter().GetResult()` — but avoid this in UI/ASP.NET contexts |

## If You Need Synchronous-Only (no async)

```csharp
// Replace Channel with BlockingCollection — still thread-safe,
// still supports CancellationToken, no async required.
private readonly BlockingCollection<string> _queue = new();

private void RunLoop()
{
    foreach (var item in _queue.GetConsumingEnumerable(_cts.Token))
        Handle(item);
}

public void Stop()
{
    _queue.CompleteAdding();
    _cts.Cancel();
    _thread?.Join(5000);
}
```

The `Channel<T>` approach is preferred for new code; `BlockingCollection<T>` is the drop-in replacement if you must keep a dedicated thread.
